LaMDA is a</text><text start="32.7" dur="1.86">chatbot – a computer programme</text><text start="34.56" dur="2.04">designed to have conversations with</text><text start="36.6" dur="1.08">humans over the internet.</text><text start="37.68" dur="2.82">After months talking with LaMDA</text><text start="40.5" dur="2.28">on topics ranging from movies to</text><text start="42.78" dur="2.22">the meaning of life, Blake came to</text><text start="45" dur="2.7">a surprising conclusion: the chatbot</text><text start="47.7" dur="2.64">was an intelligent person with wishes</text><text start="50.34" dur="2.16">and rights that should be respected.</text><text start="52.5" dur="2.64">For Blake, LaMDA was a Google</text><text start="55.14" dur="1.38">employee, not a machine.</text><text start="56.52" dur="2.16">He also called it his ‘friend’.</text><text start="58.68" dur="2.58">Google quickly reassigned Blake from</text><text start="61.26" dur="1.86">the project, announcing that his ideas</text><text start="63.12" dur="2.22">were not supported by the evidence.</text><text start="65.34" dur="2.7">But what exactly was going on?</text><text start="68.04" dur="1.86">In this programme, we’ll be</text><text start="69.9" dur="2.16">discussing whether artificial intelligence</text><text start="72.06" dur="3">is capable of consciousness. We’ll hear</text><text start="75.06" dur="3">from one expert who thinks AI is not as</text><text start="78.06" dur="1.56">intelligent as we sometimes think,</text><text start="79.62" dur="2.46">and as usual, we’ll be learning some</text><text start="82.08" dur="1.32">new vocabulary as well.</text><text start="83.4" dur="2.1">But before that, I have a question for</text><text start="85.5" dur="2.28">you, Neil. What happened to Blake Lemoine</text><text start="87.78" dur="2.94">is strangely similar to the 2013 Hollywood</text><text start="90.72" dur="3.42">movie, Her, starring Joaquin Phoenix as</text><text start="94.14" dur="1.86">a lonely writer who talks with his</text><text start="96" dur="2.28">computer, voiced by Scarlett Johansson.</text><text start="98.28" dur="1.86">But what happens at the end</text><text start="100.14" dur="1.38">of the movie? Is it:</text><text start="101.52" dur="1.86">a) the computer comes to life?</text><text start="103.38" dur="3.36">b) the computer dreams about the writer? or,</text><text start="106.74" dur="2.04">c) the writer falls in love with the computer?</text><text start="108.78" dur="3.42">... c) the writer falls in love with the computer.</text><text start="112.2" dur="2.7">OK, Neil, I’ll reveal the answer at the end</text><text start="114.9" dur="2.46">of the programme. Although Hollywood is</text><text start="117.36" dur="2.34">full of movies about robots coming to life,</text><text start="119.7" dur="3.24">Emily Bender, a professor of linguistics and</text><text start="122.94" dur="2.1">computing at the University of Washington,</text><text start="125.04" dur="4.44">thinks AI isn’t that smart. She thinks the</text><text start="129.48" dur="1.8">words we use to talk about technology,</text><text start="131.28" dur="3.3">phrases like ‘machine learning’, give a</text><text start="134.58" dur="1.62">false impression about what</text><text start="136.2" dur="1.74">computers can and can’t do.</text><text start="137.94" dur="2.4">Here is Professor Bender discussing</text><text start="140.34" dur="2.34">another misleading phrase, ‘speech</text><text start="142.68" dur="2.46">recognition’, with BBC World Service</text><text start="145.14" dur="1.44">programme, The Inquiry:</text><text start="147.36" dur="2.22">If you talk about ‘automatic speech</text><text start="149.58" dur="1.92">recognition’, the term ‘recognition’</text><text start="151.5" dur="2.1">suggests that there&#39;s something</text><text start="153.6" dur="2.16">cognitive going on, where I think a</text><text start="155.76" dur="2.1">better term would be automatic transcription.</text><text start="157.86" dur="1.98">That just describes the input-output</text><text start="159.84" dur="3.66">relation, and not any theory or wishful</text><text start="163.5" dur="2.28">thinking about what the computer is</text><text start="165.78" dur="1.44">doing to be able to achieve that.</text><text start="167.22" dur="3.36">Using words like ‘recognition’ in relation</text><text start="170.58" dur="2.1">to computers gives the idea that</text><text start="172.68" dur="2.76">something cognitive is happening – something</text><text start="175.44" dur="2.34">related to the mental processes of</text><text start="177.78" dur="2.76">thinking, knowing, learning and understanding.</text><text start="180.54" dur="2.7">But thinking and knowing are human,</text><text start="183.24" dur="3.06">not machine, activities. Professor Benders</text><text start="186.3" dur="2.04">says that talking about them in connection</text><text start="188.34" dur="3.57">with computers is wishful thinking -</text><text start="191.91" dur="2.31">something which is unlikely to happen.</text><text start="194.22" dur="2.22">The problem with using words in this</text><text start="196.44" dur="2.1">way is that it reinforces what</text><text start="198.54" dur="2.16">Professor Bender calls, technical</text><text start="200.7" dur="2.52">bias – the assumption that the computer</text><text start="203.22" dur="2.52">is always right. When we encounter</text><text start="205.74" dur="1.68">language that sounds natural, but is</text><text start="207.42" dur="2.28">coming from a computer, humans</text><text start="209.7" dur="2.46">can’t help but imagine a mind behind</text><text start="212.16" dur="2.22">the language, even when there isn’t one.</text><text start="214.38" dur="2.16">In other words, we anthropomorphise</text><text start="216.54" dur="2.52">computers – we treat them as if they</text><text start="219.06" dur="2.22">were human. Here’s Professor Bender</text><text start="221.28" dur="2.22">again, discussing this idea with</text><text start="223.5" dur="2.7">Charmaine Cozier, presenter of BBC</text><text start="226.2" dur="1.62">World Service’s, the Inquiry.</text><text start="228.42" dur="3.66">So ‘ism’ means system, ‘anthro’ or ‘anthropo’</text><text start="232.08" dur="3">means human, and ‘morph’ means shape...</text><text start="235.08" dur="3">And so this is a system that puts the</text><text start="238.08" dur="2.16">shape of a human on something, and</text><text start="240.24" dur="1.26">in this case the something is a computer.</text><text start="241.5" dur="3.18">We anthropomorphise animals all the time,</text><text start="244.68" dur="3.06">but we also anthropomorphise action figures,</text><text start="247.74" dur="2.88">or dolls, or companies when we talk about</text><text start="250.62" dur="2.04">companies having intentions and so on.</text><text start="252.66" dur="2.88">We very much are in the habit of seeing</text><text start="255.54" dur="1.62">ourselves in the world around us.</text><text start="257.16" dur="2.22">And while we’re busy seeing ourselves</text><text start="259.38" dur="2.1">by assigning human traits to things that</text><text start="261.48" dur="2.52">are not, we risk being blindsided.</text><text start="264" dur="2.4">The more fluent that text is, the more</text><text start="266.4" dur="2.7">different topics it can converse on, the</text><text start="269.1" dur="1.92">more chances there are to get taken in.</text><text start="271.86" dur="2.76">If we treat computers as if they could think,</text><text start="274.62" dur="2.52">we might get blindsided, or</text><text start="277.14" dur="3.18">unpleasantly surprised. Artificial intelligence</text><text start="280.32" dur="2.22">works by finding patterns in massive</text><text start="282.54" dur="2.52">amounts of data, so it can seem like</text><text start="285.06" dur="1.86">we’re talking with a human, instead</text><text start="286.92" dur="2.22">of a machine doing data analysis.</text><text start="289.14" dur="4.02">As a result, we get taken in – we’re tricked</text><text start="293.16" dur="1.92">or deceived into thinking we’re dealing</text><text start="295.08" dur="3.003">with a human, or with something intelligent.</text><text start="298.083" dur="3.318">Powerful AI can make machines appear conscious,</text><text start="301.401" dur="2.945">but even tech giants like Google are years</text><text start="304.346" dur="2.407">away from building computers that can</text><text start="306.753" dur="2.355">dream or fall in love. title: Beste Mark Rutte, zo klink je als je #klimaatleiderschap toont
description: Stel dat Nederland een premier zou hebben die het klimaat wél serieus neemt, dan zou je vandaag deze toespraak horen.

Specifically,</text><text start="119.777" dur="2.871">the time allocation for each light signal</text><text start="122.648" dur="1.533">at an intersection with a cycle of 120 seconds</text><text start="124.181" dur="2.635">is usually 55 seconds for a green light, 3 seconds for a yellow light, 2</text><text start="126.816" dur="2.738">seconds for a full red light, and 60 seconds for a red light.</text><text start="129.554" dur="1.416">In other words, the longer the period, the longer</text><text start="130.97" dur="1.853">each light signal will be.</text><text start="132.823" dur="1.917">The second term is &quot;time phase&quot;.</text><text start="134.74" dur="3.186">&quot;Time phase&quot; refers to the direction of traffic flow when the green light is released.</text><text start="137.926" dur="1.817">For example, a general intersection</text><text start="139.743" dur="3.119">will go east-west, then switch to north-south, and go</text><text start="142.862" dur="3.303">north-south . After the light turns green and then changes to the east-west direction</text><text start="146.165" dur="2.302">, it is a &quot;two-phase&quot; intersection</text><text start="148.467" dur="3.001">[Why does the red light take so long? 】</text><text start="151.468" dur="1.318">The general design principle of traffic lights</text><text start="152.786" dur="1.783">is to &quot;reduce the number of phases.&quot;</text><text start="154.569" dur="2.152">Because if you can pass in a certain direction,</text><text start="156.721" dur="2.786">it means that you can&#39;t go in other directions at the same intersection.</text><text start="159.507" dur="1.802">So if there are too many phases at an intersection,</text><text start="161.309" dur="2.735">cars in other directions will be blocked.
